      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Saul Blitz was an American businessman and manufacturer in the plastics industry.  In the mid-1950s, Saul Blitz took 
over TICO Plastics, a division of NOMA (a plastics molding plant that made plastic light shades, 
decorations and novelty item components to NOMA Lites) in a leveraged buy out. TICO Plastics became 
financially independent of NOMA Electric Corporation and NOMA Lites Incorporated. The factory 
continued in operation at 55 West 13th Street in New York City until 1971.</p>
</bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Saul Blitz Collection of Plastics Patents</emph> contains copies of patents from the 
United States Patent Office for processes, materials and machinery used in creating, shaping &amp; molding 
plastic. It also includes one folder of correspondence from Arthur Cyr to Saul Blitz about blow molding 
patents.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
